land","England":"England","England and France":"Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Beddington, Surrey, England":"Beddington, Surrey, England"},"en":{"about 1390–October 1430":"about 1390–October 1430","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1390–1434":"1390–1434","1398–1458":"1398–1458","1338–1450":"1338–1450","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1363–1432":"1363–1432","1362–1451":"1362–1451","October 1430":"October 1430","about 1390":"about 1390","From 1420 to 1430":"from 1420 to 1430","1451":"1451","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1390":"1390","Abt 1415":"about 1415","1338":"1338","1458":"1458","about 1418":"about 1418","1434":"1434","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","circa 1415":"about 1415","before May 1374":"before May 1374","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","England":"England","England and France":"France","France":"France","Beddington, Surrey, England":"Beddington, Surrey, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, James Patrick, Kieran.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire): habitational name from any of various minor places in Wales, in particular one near Pembroke with a major castle, named from Welsh <i>caer</i> ‘fort’ + <i>rhiw</i> ‘hill, slope’. The surname was taken to Ireland soon after the Norman invasion of England and was Gaelicized as <b>de Carrún</b>. In the 16th century a family called <i>Carew</i> from Devon played an important part in establishing the Tudor administration in Ireland.","Cornish (Somerset and Devon): from the cognate Cornish word <i>kerrow</i> (plural of <i>ker</i> ‘fort’), which occurs seven times as a placename in Cornwall."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Carew was born about 1390, his father, Nicholas Carew Esq., was 29 and his mother, Isabel De La Mare, was 29. He married Agnes Hayton about 1418, in Beddington, Surrey, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He registered for military service in 1414. He was buried in Beddington, Surrey, England."},"et":{"about 1390–October 1430":"umbes 1390–oktoober 1430","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1390–1434":"1390–1434","1398–1458":"1398–1458","1338–1450":"1338–1450","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1363–1432":"1363–1432","1362–1451":"1362–1451","October 1430":"oktoober 1430","about 1390":"umbes 1390","From 1420 to 1430":"1420 kuni 1430","1451":"1451","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1390":"1390","Abt 1415":"umbes 1415","1338":"1338","1458":"1458","about 1418":"umbes 1418","1434":"1434","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","circa 1415":"umbes 1415","before May 1374":"enne maid 1374","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","England":"England","England and France":"Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Beddington, Surrey, England":"Beddington, Surrey, England"},"fi":{"about 1390–October 1430":"noin 1390–lokakuu 1430","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1390–1434":"1390–1434","1398–1458":"1398–1458","1338–1450":"1338–1450","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1363–1432":"1363–1432","1362–1451":"1362–1451","October 1430":"lokakuu 1430","about 1390":"noin 1390","From 1420 to 1430":"vuodesta 1420 vuoteen 1430","1451":"1451","1363":"1363","1362":"1362","1472":"1472","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1390":"1390","Abt 1415":"noin 1415","1338":"133